Rating: 4
This gazpacho was AMAZING!!! I used the ripest heirloom tomatoes in a variety of colors (orange, yellow, green, purple) and it was exactly the recipe needed to highlight the naturally sweet and fresh flavor of the fruit. For those who had trouble with solids I would recommend cutting the tomatoes in half crosswise then rubbing the cut sides of the tomatoes against the large holes of a box grater. Grate into a large bowl, reserving pulp. The skin will not go through and you can discard it without having to boil and peel tomatoes. After pureeing in the food processor I just gently shook the soup through a strainer and the only thing left behind were the seeds. Afterwards, I took others suggestions and tossed some avocado, lemon, oil and a pinch of the garlic/salt paste and pureed separately in a food processor. I then piped the mixture through a pastry bag to create small decorative avocado dollops. I then sprinkled finely minced red and yellow peppers and a bit of cucumber on top. The resulting colors and flavors were a big WOW!

Rating: 3
I think this is a good soup, it turned out well even though I accidentally misread the recipe. {Sadly at 44 the eyes aren't what they used to be} and I accidentally added one TABLESPOON sugar, instead of a teaspoon of it. The soup still came out very good even though on the sweet side. Next time I will put in the correct sugar. I used Italian EVOO, its all I had on hand. I'm going to get the Andalusian kind in the future if I can find it.I also toasted the cumin seed before I ground it {as is done in Indian cooking} to bring out the flavor of the cumin. Tonight when I serve this I will use a little minced jalapeno for some kick and to counteract the over sweetness I accidentally created by accidentally adding to much sugar. I blanched the tomatoes, removed skin and used a food mill to de-seed the tomatoes. I put the soup through and ordinary mesh strainer at the very end which resulted in a fine texture.I know I will be making this soup many more times in the future!

