Rating: 4
My changes: I doubled the recipe, but used only 1/2 tsp cumin for the entire batch, added _no_ olive oil, and did not use peppers as a garnish. Now that that's over...This recipe is to DIE for. Like most people, I enjoy a good gazpacho on occasion, but this--this I could live on. Die, live, I realize I'm being contradictory here. Let's put it this way: I want to eat this every day for the rest of my life! Since andalusian gazpacho is meant to highlight olive oil in addition to tomato and sherry vinegar, this is what I did for a garnish: I pureed the flesh from one avocado with a bit of fresh lemon juice and olive oil (enough of each so that both can be tasted in the mixture). Then I dumped it in a ziploc, cut off the tip, and squeezed a pinwheel design onto the center of the soup. In the center of the pinwheel, I put a few drops of olive oil. The result is a less fatty soup that still delivers the fruity punch of a good olive oil. I can guarantee that I'll be making this again and again. You should too. Just be sure to let the tomatoes ripen well before using them, so you can really appreciate this soup!

